{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}} {{Infobox building | name = Palace of Culture and Science | native_name = ''Pałac Kultury i Nauki – PKiN'' | image = 20 PKiN Warszawa 270915.jpg | image_size = 240px | caption = | location = [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]] | address = [[Parade Square|Plac Defilad]] 1 | coordinates = {{coord|52|13|54|N|21|00|23|E|region:PL_scale:2000|display=inline,title}} | start_date = 2 May 1952 | completion_date = 22 July 1955 | building_type = Multi-function | roof = {{convert|187.68|m|abbr=on}} | antenna_spire = {{convert|237|m|abbr=on}} | architectural = {{convert|237|m|abbr=on}}
| observatory = {{convert|114|m|abbr=on}} | floor_count = 42 | floor_area = {{convert|123084|m2|sqft|0|abbr=on}} | architect = [[Lev Vladimirovich Rudnev|Lev Rudnev]] | architectural_style = [[Socialist realism]] | website = {{URL|http://www.pkin.pl/}} | number_of_rooms = 3288 }}
'''Palace of Culture and Science''' ({{lang-pl|Pałac Kultury i Nauki}}; abbreviated '''''PKiN''''') is a notable high-rise building in [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]]. Constructed in 1955, it is the center for various companies, public institutions and cultural activities such as concerts, cinemas, theaters, libraries, sports clubs, universities, scientific institutions and authorities of the [[Polish Academy of Sciences]]. Motivated by Polish historicism and American [[art deco]] high-rise buildings, the PKiN was designed by Soviet architect [[Lev Rudnev]] in [[Seven Sisters (Moscow)|"Seven Sisters"]] style and is informally referred to as the ''[[Eighth Sister]]''.
The Palace of Culture and Science is the tallest building in Poland, the [[List of tallest buildings in the European Union|eighth-tallest building]] in the [[European Union]] and one of the [[List of tallest buildings in Europe|tallest on the European continent]]. It is {{convert|237|m}} tall.<ref>[http://www.pkin.pl/historia-palacu/ "History of the Palace"], at the official website (retrieved March 22, 2016)</ref>
==History==
===Name=== The building was originally known as the Joseph Stalin Palace of Culture and Science (''Pałac Kultury i Nauki imienia Józefa Stalina''), but in the wake of [[destalinization]] the dedication to [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] was revoked.<ref name="Palace-2" >{{cite web|url=http://www.bestufs.net/download/conferences/Warsaw_May07/BESTUFS_Warsaw_May07_Conference_Leaflet.pdf |publisher=Best Urban Freight Solutions |title=Warsaw Palace of Culture and Science |date=24 May 2007 |format=PDF }}</ref> Stalin's name was removed from the colonnade, interior lobby and one of the building's sculptures.
Varsovians still commonly use nicknames to refer to the palace, notably ''Pekin'' ("[[Beijing]]", because of its abbreviated name ''PKiN''), and ''Pajac'' ("clown", a word that sounds close to ''Pałac''). Other less common names include ''Stalin's syringe'', the ''Elephant in Lacy Underwear'', ''Russian Wedding Cake'', or even ''Ch.j Stalina'' (Stalin's D..k").<ref>{{cite web|author =|url =http://www.whatsonwhen.com/sisp/index.htm?fx=destination&loc_id=135388&sub_section=Don't+Miss|title =Warsaw: Don't Miss|work =www.whatsonwhen.com|publisher =|pages =|page =|date =|accessdate =25 July 2008|deadurl =yes|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20110816144716/http://www.whatsonwhen.com/sisp/index.htm?fx=destination&loc_id=135388&sub_section=Don%27t+Miss|archivedate =16 August 2011|df =dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author = Małgorzata Barwicka |url =http://www.tc.ciechanow.pl/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=4422|title = Pałac pod lupą |work = www.tc.ciechanow.pl |publisher = Tygodnik Ciechanowski |pages = |page = |date = 7 March 2007 |accessdate = 29 July 2008|language=pl}}</ref>
However, only ''Pekin'' was the popular alternative name. Also, despite some later confusion, the name ''patyk'' (a Polish word for stick) didn't stand for PKiN but for the {{convert|10|m|ft|adj=mid|-high}} signpost, in the corner of the [[Parade Square]], near the intersection of [[Marszałkowska Street]] and [[Jerusalem Avenue]]. The four walls of the signpost display the names of several large or important cities around the world, together with the distances from the signpost itself.
===Construction=== [[File:Pałac Kultury i Nauki - 01.jpg|thumb|left|South view of the Palace]] Construction started in 1952 and lasted until 1955. A gift from the Soviet Union to the people of Poland, the tower was constructed, using Soviet plans, by 3,500 to 5,000 Russian workers and 4,000 Polish workers. Sixteen workers died in accidents during the construction.<ref name="history">{{cite web |author = |url = http://www.pkin.pl/historia/ |title = History of PKiN in a nutshell |work = www.pkin.pl |publisher = |pages = |page = |date = |accessdate = 25 July 2008}}</ref> The Russian builders were housed at a new suburban complex built at Poland's expense, with its own cinema, food court, community centre and swimming pool, called Osiedle "Przyjaźni" (Neighborhood of Friendship).<ref name="Palace-2"/><ref>[http://www.pkin.pl/historia/ Pałac Kultury i Nauki "Historia"] at the PKN official website.</ref> The architecture of the building is closely related to [[Seven Sisters (Moscow)|several similar skyscrapers]] built in the Soviet Union of the same era, most notably the [[Main building of Moscow State University]]. However, the main architect [[Lev Vladimirovich Rudnev|Lev Rudnev]] incorporated some Polish architectural details into the project after traveling around Poland and seeing the architecture.<ref name="history" /> The monumental walls are headed with pieces of masonry copied from [[Renaissance]] houses and palaces of [[Kraków]] and [[Zamość]].<ref name="history" />
Shortly after opening, the building hosted the [[5th World Festival of Youth and Students]]. Many visiting dignitaries toured the Palace, and it also hosted performances by notable international artists, such as a 1967 concert by [[The Rolling Stones]], the first by a major western rock group behind the [[Iron Curtain]].<ref>{{cite web |author = Timothy Tilghman |url = http://rockontour.net/bj67.html |title = The Stones Tumultuous 1967 European Tour |work = rockontour.net |publisher = |pages = |page = |date = |accessdate = 25 July 2008}}</ref> In 1985, it hosted the historic [[Leonard Cohen]] concert, surrounded by many political expectations, which were avoided by Cohen in his prolonged introductions during the three-hour show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leonardcohenfiles.com/warsaw85.html |title=Leonard Cohen in Warsaw (1985) by Daniel Wyszogrodzki |publisher=Leonardcohenfiles.com |date=22 March 1985 |accessdate=29 October 2012}}</ref>
Four {{convert|6.3|m|adj=mid}} clock faces were added to the top of the building ahead of the millennium celebrations in 2000.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}
===Present day=== [[File:Pałac Kultury i Nauki i diabelski młyn.jpg|thumb|The Palace of Culture and Science at night during Christmas market]] [[File:Flickr - europeanpeoplesparty - EPP Congress in Warsaw (65).jpg|thumb|left|[[Congress Hall (Warsaw)|Congress Hall]]]] The building currently serves as an exhibition center and office complex. The Palace contains a [[multiplex (movie theater)|multiplex cinema]] with eight screens,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kinoteka.pl/wynajem-sal-1/wynajem-sal/ |title=Kinoteka: Wynajem sal |accessdate=29 January 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130003851/http://www.kinoteka.pl/wynajem-sal-1/wynajem-sal/ |archivedate=30 January 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> four theaters (Studio, Dramatyczny, Lalka and 6. piętro), two museums (Museum of Evolution and Museum of Technology), offices, bookshops, a large swimming pool, an auditorium hall for 3,000 people called [[Congress Hall (Warsaw)|Congress Hall]],<ref name="Palace-1">{{cite web|url=http://www.hum.au.dk/ckulturf/pages/publications/mz/architect.htm |title=The Height of (Architectural) Seduction: Reading the "Changes" through Stalin's Palace in Warsaw, Poland |author=Magdalena J. Zaborowska |accessdate=18 April 2008 |publisher=Centre for Cultural Research, [[University of Aarhus]] }}</ref> and an accredited university, [[Collegium Civitas]], on the 11th and 12th floors of the building. The terrace on the 30th floor, at {{convert|114|m}}, is a well-known [[tourism|tourist]] attraction with a panoramic view of the city.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}
The [[Congress Hall (Warsaw)|Congress Hall]] held the finals of [[Miss World 2006]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}
In 2010, the illumination of the building was modernized and high-power LED lights were installed, allowing the Palace to take various colours at night.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wiadomosci.onet.pl/warszawa/stolica-ponad-dwa-miliony-na-oswietlenie-palacu-kultury/zhmf2 |title=Stolica: ponad dwa miliony na oświetlenie Pałacu Kultury |language=pl |publisher=Onet Wiadomości |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> The first use of the new lighting was during Christmas in 2010, when the Palace was illuminated in green and white to resemble a Christmas tree.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rmf24.pl/fakty/polska/news-swiateczne-oswietlenie-palacu-kultury-i-nauki-w-warszawie,nId,314488 |title=Świąteczne oświetlenie Pałacu Kultury i Nauki w Warszawie |publisher=RMF24.pl |language=pl |date=23 December 2010 |accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> In December 2013, during the [[Euromaidan]] protests, it was illuminated in yellow and blue, the colors of the [[Flag of Ukraine|Ukrainian national flag]] as a sign of solidarity with the protesters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://warszawa.gazeta.pl/warszawa/1,95080,15076004,Palac_Kultury_podswietlony_w_barwach_Ukrainy__ZDJECIA_.html |title=Pałac Kultury podświetlony w barwach Ukrainy [ZDJĘCIA] |publisher=Wyborcza.pl Warszawa |language=pl |date=5 December 2013 |accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref>
